To draw a chessboard using FEN notation in LaTeX, you can use the `xskak` package. Here's an example code that sets up the board with a given FEN notation:
```latex
\usepackage{xskak}

\begin{document}
\setboard{fen=rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2.}
\end{document}
```
In this example, the `fen=` parameter specifies the FEN notation of the board state. The `w KQkq - 0 2.` part at the end of the FEN string represents the side to move (white in this case), the castling availability (KQkq), the en passant target square (none in this case, represented by '-'), and the halfmove clock (0).

To compile this code, you'll need to save it in a file with a `.tex` extension (e.g., `chessboard.tex`) and then run Latex on it (e.g., using the command `pdflatex chessboard`). This will produce a PDF file that displays the chessboard with the specified FEN notation.

